    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-13T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-13T12:00:00-05:00" n="633"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d633">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">816.00/847: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in El Salvador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MWJ1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McCafferty</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San Salvador</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-13T11:00:00-06:00"
                            >February 13, 1932—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 3:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>41. My telegram No. 38, February 12, 3 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <item>First Designate, <persName corresp="#p_GCFC1">Garay</persName>, who has
                        been Commandant of the Department of San Miguel since March 1931 has under
                        his chargé between 100 and 200 troops, therefore he does not have a high
                        military command. He had no connection with the military <hi rend="italic"
                            >coup d’état</hi> of December 2nd and is not related to any of the
                        leaders thereof.</item>
                    <item>Second Designate, <persName corresp="#p_FCCB1">Flores</persName>, was
                        Chief of the Topographical Section of the War Department at the time of the
                        recent revolution and was appointed Under Secretary of Fomento on December
                        9, 1931. He has not held any high military command, took no part in the <hi
                            rend="italic">coup d’état</hi> and is not related to any of the leaders
                        thereof.</item>
                    <item>Third Designate, <persName corresp="#p_PGAJ1">Pinto</persName>, is Chief
                        of the Personnel Section of the Ministry of War which position he held prior
                        to the revolution of December 2nd. He was not connected with the recent <hi
                            rend="italic">coup d’état</hi>, has not held any high military command
                        and is not related to any of the revolutionary leaders.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Repeated to all Legations in Central America.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">McCafferty</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
